^*Bhondo717:^*N Well, aggie started off with a big bang. nice going. First the auction. one question is should aggie open with 1@C or 1@H. There are two schools of thought here. Theoretically, since aggie's hand is strong enough for a reverse, she could start with a club and bid hearts twice. However, because it is a distributional hand, it is likely the opponents may gum up the works by preempting. So, there is a strong case to be made for aggie opening one heart, as that gets her 5 card major across ASAP. It is really a question of tactics.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N Now, let us continue with the rest of the bidding.  kia could certainly bid 2@D, and I think he should. He has a very good 6 card suit and 9 HCP. Doesn't make a difference on this hand, as I still bid 2@H. The most important bid was aggie's 4@H bid.  Although she only has 13 HCP, she has a hand worth at least 20 points, particularly once I raise her bid. Two suited hands are extremely powerful, and aggie showed excellent judgement by bidding 4@H.  So, the bidding was generally good.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N As to the play. First, the opening lead.  Against a suit contract, it is never right to under lead an ace. It could easily give up a trick. Granted in this case, since joyce overcalled spades, the risk is low, but it is there. So, once kia chooses to lead a spade, and that is good since joyce bid them, he should lead the ace. Now, one other comment on the play. If you recall aggie, joyce led back a heart at trick two.   |
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N Although it probably doesn't matter, there are at least 2 reasons to play low.  In this particular case, the more important reason is that it lets you pick up the suit even if kia has 4 to the J.  And secondly, in general, when playing a suit, you cash the honors in the short hand first.  The reason for that is you don't have to waste entries getting back to your hand. If you cash the honors in the long hand first, you risk the danger of blocking the suit. In general, when you are cashing a suit, play the honors in the hand shorter in that suit first.  Next board please.|
