^*Bhondo717:^*N This is a pretty interesting hand, both bidding and defense. First, let me deal with the bidding.  kia's 2 spade bid shows a limit raise. He is right on the border of 3@H and 2@S.  He has 10 HCP, but the K of clubs and Q of spades do not pull their full weight in general. On this hand they are both good cards, but given the auction, the Q of spades may not be useful, and hard to say about the K of clubs. So, 2@S is reasonable, but so is 3@H, which would show 4 card support and less than a limit raise.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N It is really a judgement call, and I would say both are equally good. Had I not bid 1@S, kia has a clear limit raise.  aggie similarly needs to devalue her spade cards, although it turns out they are valuable. So, 3@H by her was fine.  As to the defense there is an interesting signaling principle here that moe was probably was not aware of.  When I led the ace of diamonds, although moe has a diamond trick, he really should play a low diamond, discouraging me from continuing. The reason is, he wants me to give him a spade ruff.  I am not likely to lead another club, as I already know aggie has the ace from trick one.  So, if he plays a low diamond, I will lead a spade most likely.|
